    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting a Standard "Golden Visa" Process</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Switzerland doesn't have an invest-X-get-residency program. It's negotiated, subjective, and depends on cantonal authorities. What works in Vaud may not work in Geneva. Engage experienced Swiss advisors—don't assume EU Golden Visa experience applies.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing a Canton That Abolished Lump-Sum</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Zurich, Basel-Stadt, and several other cantons have abolished lump-sum taxation. If you're set on Zurich or Basel, you'll pay full Swiss taxes on worldwide income. Research cantonal rules before committing to a location.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Planning to Work in Switzerland</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Lump-sum taxation specifically prohibits working in Switzerland or earning Swiss-source income. Board seats, consulting, employment—all would revoke your forfait status. If you need to work, you need a different visa category and will pay regular taxation.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Mandatory Health Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Switzerland requires LAMal enrollment within 3 months—no exceptions for wealthy residents. International insurance doesn't count. Failure to enroll results in automatic assignment to an insurer at premium rates. Arrange this properly and budget CHF 350-600/month per person.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Cost of Living</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Switzerland is 50-100% more expensive than most of Europe. A CHF 400,000 tax bill is just the start. Add CHF 150,000-300,000 for living expenses, CHF 15,000-25,000 for insurance, and property costs. Total outlay easily exceeds CHF 600,000-1,000,000 annually.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
