  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How much wealth do I need for Swiss residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          There's no official minimum, but practically speaking, you need CHF 10M+ in assets to make lump-sum taxation worthwhile. The minimum annual tax is CHF 400,000+, and living costs in Switzerland are extremely high. Most forfait residents have CHF 20M+ in assets.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work in Switzerland with lump-sum taxation?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Lump-sum taxation specifically prohibits gainful employment in Switzerland or earning Swiss-source income. If you work, consult, or earn Swiss income, your forfait status is revoked and you pay regular Swiss taxes on worldwide income. Structure carefully if you have any ongoing business activities.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Swiss health insurance really mandatory?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Absolutely. ALL Swiss residents must enroll in basic health insurance (LAMal) within 3 months. There are no exceptions for wealthy residents. International insurance does not satisfy this requirement. Failure to enroll results in automatic assignment to an insurer with penalty premiums.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get Swiss citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Naturalization requires 10+ years of residence (Permit C eligibility after 10 years, then citizenship application). You must pass language tests (B1 in local language), integration assessments, and meet other criteria. Lump-sum residents can naturalize, but the process scrutinizes integration carefully.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I live in Zurich with lump-sum taxation?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Zurich abolished lump-sum taxation in 2009. If you want to live in Zurich, you'll pay regular Swiss taxes on worldwide income. For forfait, consider: Geneva, Vaud, Valais, Ticino, Zug, or other cantons that still offer it. Each has different character and minimums.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does Switzerland compare to Monaco for wealthy residents?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Monaco has no income tax—zero. Switzerland has significant tax (CHF 400K+ minimum). But Switzerland offers: larger country, more diverse lifestyle options, better infrastructure, and full Schengen access. Monaco is smaller, more focused on Mediterranean lifestyle. Choose based on preferred lifestyle and tax optimization needs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

